in the back of their mind

00:03:22.570 --> 00:03:24.880
where they felt
like being too nice

00:03:24.880 --> 00:03:28.690
has kept them out of
an opportunity at work?

00:03:28.690 --> 00:03:30.700
And we're all in this
room for a reason, right?

00:03:30.700 --> 00:03:32.920
It's really something
where I think

00:03:32.920 --> 00:03:35.050
our culture here
at Google really

00:03:35.050 --> 00:03:37.330
wants everyone to
bring your full self

00:03:37.330 --> 00:03:40.970
and to have the psychological
safety to share your opinions.

00:03:40.970 --> 00:03:42.997
And so with that, you
think it's kindness.

00:03:42.997 --> 00:03:44.830
But the truth is in
business, sometimes, you

00:03:44.830 --> 00:03:47.120
feel like that could
be a liability.

00:03:47.120 --> 00:03:48.910
So in your book
you talk about how

00:03:48.910 --> 00:03:52.660
the word nice is emotionally
loaded, particularly for women.

00:03:52.660 --> 00:03:56.140
I would love to hear how
you define being nice.

00:03:56.140 --> 00:03:58.370
FRAN HAUSER: So specifically
when it comes to work,

00:03:58.370 --> 00:04:01.780
when I think about
a woman or a man,

00:04:01.780 --> 00:04:05.860
actually, who's in a
professional environment,

00:04:05.860 --> 00:04:09.970
and they're nice, I think about
somebody who is empathetic,

00:04:09.970 --> 00:04:14.890
who's collaborative,
and who's confident

00:04:14.890 --> 00:04:18.040
that there are enough
opportunities to go around.

00:04:18.040 --> 00:04:20.140
And I think that last
part is really important,

00:04:20.140 --> 00:04:24.070
because that's really more of
an abundance mentality, where

00:04:24.070 --> 00:04:28.270
it's not like, if you win,
it means that I have to lose.

00:04:28.270 --> 00:04:31.100
There's a real generosity
that comes with that.

00:04:31.100 --> 00:04:34.060
And the premise of
the book is actually

00:04:34.060 --> 00:04:37.480
really simple, in
that if you're nice,

00:04:37.480 --> 00:04:39.490
if you do all those
things, you're empathetic,

00:04:39.490 --> 00:04:42.280
you're collaborative,
you're generous,

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:45.640
what that does is
it engenders trust.

00:04:45.640 --> 00:04:47.890
And when you have
trust, that allows

00:04:47.890 --> 00:04:49.640
you to build a relationship.

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:52.240
And at the end of the day,
being successful in business

00:04:52.240 --> 00:04:54.190
is all about relationships.

00:04:54.190 --> 00:04:56.440
It all comes back
to relationships.

00:04:56.440 --> 00:04:58.780
And the other big
message in the book

00:04:58.780 --> 00:05:02.680
is that you don't have to choose
between being nice and being

00:05:02.680 --> 00:05:03.820
tough.

00:05:03.820 --> 00:05:06.050
You can be both.

00:05:06.050 --> 00:05:07.990
And there's that duality
that I think really

00:05:07.990 --> 00:05:10.300
runs throughout the whole book.

00:05:10.300 --> 00:05:13.090
So when I'm talking about
communication it's-- you can be

00:05:13.090 --> 00:05:14.740
kind and direct.

00:05:14.740 --> 00:05:17.620
When you're negotiating, you
can be empathetic and strategic.

00:05:17.620 --> 00:05:21.610
So these things aren't
mutually exclusive.

00:05:21.610 --> 00:05:24.181
SPEAKER: It's a very
important point.

00:05:24.181 --> 00:05:25.180
FRAN HAUSER: Are you OK?

00:05:25.180 --> 00:05:26.480
