00:05:38.380 --> 00:05:42.640
where we kind of walked
around an imaginary forest.

00:05:42.640 --> 00:05:44.650
And you were holding
an imaginary stick

00:05:44.650 --> 00:05:45.850
in this imaginary forest.

00:05:45.850 --> 00:05:48.370
And that imaginary stick
was your greatest strength.

00:05:48.370 --> 00:05:49.870
And so you walked
around the forest.

00:05:49.870 --> 00:05:51.730
You were talking with other
people in the program.

00:05:51.730 --> 00:05:52.940
You had your stick with you.

00:05:52.940 --> 00:05:54.439
So you're really
thinking about what

00:05:54.439 --> 00:05:56.260
this greatest strength was.

00:05:56.260 --> 00:05:59.110
And then they asked you
to think about a time

00:05:59.110 --> 00:06:01.510
when that stick had become
your greatest weakness.

00:06:01.510 --> 00:06:04.040
And how do you set that down?

00:06:04.040 --> 00:06:06.400
So it's a really
interesting exercise.

00:06:06.400 --> 00:06:09.670
But in the book Fran
talked about empathy

00:06:09.670 --> 00:06:11.480
being your Achilles heel.

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:14.140
And I would love to
hear more about that.

00:06:14.140 --> 00:06:16.810
FRAN HAUSER: Well, I
over-index on empathy.

00:06:16.810 --> 00:06:20.290
And while empathy is
an incredible, I think,

00:06:20.290 --> 00:06:23.840
trait, where it has
hurt me in the past

00:06:23.840 --> 00:06:28.780
is when I care so much about
what other people are feeling

00:06:28.780 --> 00:06:31.900
and thinking that it
makes it difficult

00:06:31.900 --> 00:06:33.484
for me to make a decision.

00:06:33.484 --> 00:06:34.900
Because when you
care so much, you

00:06:34.900 --> 00:06:36.040
want to make everybody happy.

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:37.123
And you're getting buy-in.

00:06:37.123 --> 00:06:39.110
And you're checking
in with everyone.

00:06:39.110 --> 00:06:41.710
And that slows down the
decision making process.

00:06:41.710 --> 00:06:46.150
And especially working in
technology or working in media,

00:06:46.150 --> 00:06:47.710
you need to move quickly.

00:06:47.710 --> 00:06:50.239
Time to market is everything.

00:06:50.239 --> 00:06:52.030
Whether it's-- you're
working on a product,

00:06:52.030 --> 00:06:54.321
and you're trying to figure
out which features to leave

00:06:54.321 --> 00:06:58.320
in and which features
get scoped out.

00:06:58.320 --> 00:07:01.117
It's really important to
keep the momentum going

00:07:01.117 --> 00:07:01.950
and to move quickly.

00:07:01.950 --> 00:07:05.530
So that's where it's
actually hurt me.

00:07:05.530 --> 00:07:07.720
And I've had to make sure
that I pull back on that.

00:07:07.720 --> 00:07:12.934
And that I really be aware of
that and be cognizant of it.

00:07:12.934 --> 00:07:13.850
SPEAKER: Amen on that.

00:07:13.850 --> 00:07:17.350
Because it is-- and I think
the nuance and the line

00:07:17.350 --> 00:07:21.557
that you're drawing here is
collaboration to a degree.

00:07:21.557 --> 00:07:23.890
At some point you've just got
to make a decision instead

00:07:23.890 --> 00:07:26.309
of waiting for a decision
to be made for you.

00:07:26.309 --> 00:07:27.850
But it's really
challenging, I think,

00:07:27.850 --> 00:07:28.980
when you're so empathetic.

00:07:28.980 --> 00:07:31.480
And you want to make sure that
everyone is feeling included,

00:07:31.480 --> 00:07:33.470
and everyone is
along for the ride.

00:07:33.470 --> 00:07:35.470
At some point,
particularly as you

00:07:35.470 --> 00:07:38.037
grow into leadership
positions in your career,

00:07:38.037 --> 00:07:40.120
people are looking to you
to make those decisions.

00:07:40.120 --> 00:07:42.453
And people are looking to you
to be that decisive voice.

00:07:42.453 --> 00:07:44.880
So it's been a very relevant
lesson for me recently.

00:07:44.880 --> 00:07:45.671
FRAN HAUSER: Right?

00:07:45.671 --> 00:07:47.770
And I think you definitely
want to show people

00:07:47.770 --> 00:07:51.550
that you're listening to them,
and that you respect them,

00:07:51.550 --> 00:07:53.050
and that you're
getting their input,

00:07:53.050 --> 00:07:55.012
and that you're
considering their input.

00:07:55.012 --> 00:07:56.470
But then at the
end of the day, you

00:07:56.470 --> 00:07:57.970
have to stand in
your own two shoes.

00:07:57.970 --> 00:07:59.900
And you have to make
that tough call.

00:07:59.900 --> 00:08:04.542
And when you inform the team
that you've made the decision,

00:08:04.542 --> 00:08:06.250
I think it's great to
say, look, I really

00:08:06.250 --> 00:08:08.249
respect what every single
one of you had to say.

00:08:08.249 --> 00:08:10.262
And I took it into
consideration.

00:08:10.262 --> 00:08:12.470
But at the same time, we
really need to move forward.

00:08:12.470 --> 00:08:13.700
And I had to make a decision.

00:08:13.700 --> 00:08:15.616
Some of you are not going
to be happy with it.

00:08:15.616 --> 00:08:17.215
But we have to move forward.

00:08:17.215 --> 00:08:17.860
SPEAKER: And I think
what I've found--

00:08:17.860 --> 00:08:18.850
FRAN HAUSER: So there is a
way-- there's a way to do it.

00:08:18.850 --> 00:08:20.425
SPEAKER: There's a
way, because actually--

00:08:20.425 --> 00:08:20.930
FRAN HAUSER: It took me
a while to figure it out.

00:08:20.930 --> 00:08:23.240
SPEAKER: --it provides relief.

00:08:23.240 --> 00:08:25.030
Even if they disagree
with the decision

00:08:25.030 --> 00:08:28.022
or feel like it's not going
in a direction they love,

00:08:28.022 --> 00:08:29.980
there's a relief that a
decision has been made.

00:08:29.980 --> 00:08:31.990
Anyway, I literally ran
out of highlighter ink

00:08:31.990 --> 00:08:32.890
in this chapter.

00:08:32.890 --> 00:08:35.540
Because this was, like I said,
just very relevant for me

00:08:35.540 --> 00:08:36.039
right now.

00:08:36.039 --> 00:08:37.809
And that's kind of
what I'm talking about.

00:08:37.809 --> 00:08:40.000
There are stages of your career
were different parts of this

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:40.708
will be relevant.

00:08:40.708 --> 00:08:43.440
And you'll remember
them to go back to.

00:08:43.440 --> 00:08:45.250
So one of my favorite
Maya Angelou quotes

00:08:45.250 --> 00:08:47.026
is the one where--

00:08:47.026 --> 00:08:48.400
and I'm going to
slaughter this--

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:50.980
but when a woman stands up for
herself, unbeknownst to her

00:08:50.980 --> 00:08:53.290
she stands up for all women.

00:08:53.290 --> 00:08:55.410
You had a great anecdote
during your time

00:08:55.410 --> 00:08:58.089
